This is a placeholder for an Excel file. In a real scenario, this would be a binary .xlsx file.

To create a real sample Excel file, use Python:

```python
import openpyxl

wb = openpyxl.Workbook()
ws = wb.active
ws.title = "Data Formats"

# Headers
ws['A1'] = 'Format'
ws['B1'] = 'Extension'
ws['C1'] = 'Parser'
ws['D1'] = 'Notes'

# Data
data = [
    ('Markdown', '.md', 'MarkdownParser', 'Preserves structure'),
    ('Plain Text', '.txt', 'TextParser', 'UTF-8 encoding'),
    ('HTML', '.html', 'HTMLParser', 'Removes scripts/styles'),
    ('PDF', '.pdf', 'PDFParser', 'Uses PyMuPDF'),
    ('Excel', '.xlsx', 'ExcelParser', 'All sheets extracted'),
]

for i, row in enumerate(data, 2):
    ws[f'A{i}'] = row[0]
    ws[f'B{i}'] = row[1]
    ws[f'C{i}'] = row[2]
    ws[f'D{i}'] = row[3]

wb.save('data-formats.xlsx')
```
